In [4]:
def metrics_bundle(index, clf, y_test, y_pred, p_pred):
    # misclf rate
    misclf = 1-accuracy_score(
        y_test, y_pred, normalize=1)
    # top1k success rate
    top1k_indices = np.argsort(-p_pred)[:1000]
    success_rate = sum(y_test[list(top1k_indices)])/1000
    # auc
    fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_test, p_pred)
    auc_score = auc(fpr, tpr)
    roc = [fpr, tpr]
    # oob error
    oob_error = np.nan
    if hasattr(clf, 'oob_score_'):
        oob_error = 1 - clf.oob_score_
    # clf position on roc curve
    est, truth = y_pred.astype(bool), y_test.astype(bool)
    n, p = len(est), np.sum(truth)
    fp = np.sum(est & (~truth))
    fn = np.sum(truth & (~est))
    tp = p - fn; tn = n - p - fp
    sens = tp/p; spec = tn/(n-p)
    roc_loc = [1-spec, sens]
    return [index, misclf, oob_error, 
            auc_score, success_rate], roc, roc_loc

Comments¶

Question (b)¶

  • The misclassification rate of the first Random Forest classifier is 0.123645. This is slightly higher than the base rate and that of benchmark classifiers. But, as discussed in last mini, we don't care the misclassification rate that much for this problem.
  • The misclassification rate is close to the OOB error, which implies that the OOB error is a good approximation to the misclf rate on validation set.
  • AUC of Random Forest (0.678699) is better than that of Logistic Regression, but a bit worse than the Logistic GAM.
  • In terms of our homemade the "top 1000 clients success rate", the Random Forest classifier (0.326) beats both of the benchmark models.

Question (c)¶

  • By setting min_samples_leaf=10, all of the metrics were improved. In particular, AUC was increased from 0.678699 to 0.712847; and "top 1000 clients success rate" was increased from 0.326 to 0.344.

Question (d)¶

  • The ROC curve itself generally does not change much, but the point on ROC curve that corresponds to the classifer shifted from left-bottom corner to the middle part of the curve dramatically after we adjusted the class weights.
  • This is due to the change of loss function that leads to a change of classification threshold, as we discussed in last mini. Essentially, adding more weights to the rare class "1" is equivalent to rising the False Negative Loss. For example: if the weights of class "1" samples is doubled, we will make 2 errors if predicting "0" for a true "1" instead of 1 error. Increasing FN loss leads to higher sensitivity (which is almost 0 previously) and lower specificity (which is almost 1 previously). Therefore, the new trade-off moves the classifier upward.
  • The misclassification rate of the rebalanced Random Forest is higher than the other models. This is natural because misclassification rate corresponds to 0-1 loss, which is no longer the optimization objective of the classifier. However, if we look at the confusion matrix, the FPs and FNs become more balanced.

def importance_plot(clf, ax, X, X_names):
    importances = clf.feature_importances_
    indices = np.argsort(importances)
    if type(clf) is RandomForestClassifier:
        std = np.std([tree.feature_importances_ 
                      for tree in clf.estimators_], axis=0)
        ax.barh(range(X.shape[1]), 
                importances[indices], 
                yerr=std[indices], align="center")
    else:
        ax.barh(range(X.shape[1]), 
                importances[indices], 
                align="center")
    ax.set_yticks(range(len(indices)))
    ax.set_yticklabels(X_names[indices])
    ax.update({'xlabel':'Relative Importance', 
               'ylabel':'Feature', 
               'title':'Feature Importances Plot'})
    return ax

In [17]:
def get_circle_data(n):
    gaussian_2d = scipy.stats.multivariate_normal(
        mean = np.zeros(2), cov = np.eye(2))
    X = gaussian_2d.rvs(n)
    Y = np.where(X[:,0]**2+X[:,1]**2<1, 1, -1)
    return(X,Y)

def find_split(X, y, wgts=None):
    n = X.shape[0]
    dtc = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=1)
    fit = dtc.fit(X,y, sample_weight=wgts)
    tree_info = {
        'variable_idx' : fit.tree_.feature[0],
        'threshold' : fit.tree_.threshold[0],
        'guess_less' : np.argmax(fit.tree_.value[1])*2-1,
        'guess_greater' : np.argmax(fit.tree_.value[2])*2-1
    }
    return(fit, tree_info)

def draw_boosted_trees(trees, X, score=None,fsize=10):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,1, figsize=(fsize,fsize))
    if score is not None:
        ax.scatter(X[:,0], X[:,1], c=score, cmap=plt.get_cmap('plasma'))
    else:
        ax.scatter(X[:,0], X[:,1])
    line_col='grey'
    for fit in trees:
        variable_idx = fit.tree_.feature[0]
        threshold = fit.tree_.threshold[0]
        if variable_idx==0:
            ax.axvline(x = threshold, color=line_col)
        else:
            ax.axhline(y = threshold, color=line_col)
    ax.update({'xlabel':'X1', 
           'ylabel':'X2', 
           'title':'Circle Data'})
    return fig, ax
In [18]:
def my_adaboost(X, y, B=10):
    n = X.shape[0]
    wgts = np.repeat(1/n, n)
    trees = []#To store your trees.  Use append()
    alphas = np.zeros(B)#To store your alphas
    bar = ProgressBar()
    for i, b in enumerate(bar(range(B))):
        tree, info = find_split(X, y, wgts)
        y_hat = tree.predict(X)
        err = wgts.dot(y_hat!=y)/np.sum(wgts)

        alphas[b] = np.log((1-err)/err)
        trees.append(tree)
        wgts = wgts * np.exp(alphas[b]*(y_hat!=y))
    return(trees, alphas)
    
def predict_ada(trees, alphas, X, y=None):
    n = X.shape[0]
    score = np.zeros(n)
    B = len(trees)
    test_err = np.zeros(B)
    for b in range(B):
        #Update your score to include the contribution from tree b
        score += alphas[b]*trees[b].predict(X)
        preds = np.sign(score)
        if y is not None:
            test_err[b] = 1-accuracy_score(
                y, preds, normalize=1)
    if y is None:
        return(score, preds)    
    return(score, preds, test_err)

def calculate_partial_dependence_x1(trees, alphas, X):
    m = 50#Number of grid points to evaluate partial dependence
    x = np.linspace(np.min(X[:,0]), np.max(X[:,0]), m)
    pdep = np.zeros(m)
    fake = X.copy()
    for i in range(m):
        fake[:,0] = x[i]
        score, preds = predict_ada(trees, alphas, fake)
        pdep[i] = np.mean(np.where(score>0,1,0))
    return(x, pdep)

In [32]:
def compare_roc(xgb_roc, xgb_loc, label='XGBoost'):
    roc_curves = [logit_roc, gam_roc, rdf_roc_curves[2], xgb_roc]
    roc_locations = [logit_loc, gam_loc, rdf_roc_locs[2], xgb_loc]
    roc_labels = ['LogisticRegression', 'LogisticGAM', 
                  'Best RandomForest', label]

    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,1, figsize=(10,10))
    for i, roc in enumerate(roc_curves):
        fpr, tpr = roc
        fpr_clf, tpr_clf = roc_locations[i]
        index = roc_labels[i]
        ax.plot(fpr, tpr, linewidth=2, label=index)
        ax.scatter(fpr_clf, tpr_clf, edgecolors='black',
                   s=180, label=index)
    ax.update({'xlabel':'FPR', 'ylabel':'TPR', 
               'title':'The ROC Curve'})
    _ = ax.legend()
    return fig, ax
fig, ax = compare_roc(xgb_roc, xgb_loc, 'Untuned XGBoost')

def fit_and_compare(clfs, X_train, y_train, 
                    X_test, y_test, 
                    refit='all', silent=[]):
    table = []
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,1, figsize=(10,10))
    for i, (name, clf) in enumerate(clfs):
        if i in silent: continue
        if refit=='all' or i in refit:
            print("Fitting", name+'...')
            clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
        else:
            print("Using fitted", name+'...')
        y_pred = clf.predict(X_test)
        if type(clf) is LogisticGAM:
            prob_pred = clf.predict_proba(X_test)
        else:
            prob_pred = clf.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]
        summary, roc, roc_loc = metrics_bundle(
            name, clf, y_test, y_pred, prob_pred)
        fpr, tpr = roc
        fpr_clf, tpr_clf = roc_loc
        ax.plot(fpr, tpr, linewidth=2, label=name)
        ax.scatter(fpr_clf, tpr_clf, edgecolors='black',
               s=180, label=name)
        table.append(summary)
    table = tabulate(table, headers=[
        'clf', 'misclf rate', 'oob error', 'auc', 'top1k success'])
    ax.update({'xlabel':'FPR', 'ylabel':'TPR', 
           'title':'The ROC Curve'})
    _ = ax.legend()
    return table, fig, ax

Freestyle Tuning: Top 1000 Success Rate¶

In [ ]:
# task 2, aiming for high Top 1000 Success rate
# We made a customized score to let the 
# GridSearchCV optimize
def top1k_success_rate(y_true, y_pred):
    p_pred = y_pred[:, 1]
    top1k_indices = np.argsort(-p_pred)[:1000]
    return sum(y_true[list(top1k_indices)])/1000

success_rate_scorer = make_scorer(
    top1k_success_rate, needs_proba=True, 
    greater_is_better=True)

xgb_clf = XGBClassifier()
param_grid = {
    'objective': ['binary:logistic'],
    'random_state': [1],
    'n_estimators': [100],
    'learning_rate': [0.05, 0.1],
    'max_depth': [8, 10, 12, 14],
    'scale_pos_weight': [1, 3, 5],
    'gamma': [0, 1, 3, 5],
    'subsample': [0.8, 0.9, 1],
    'min_child_weight': [1, 3]
}
kfold = StratifiedKFold(
    n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=1)
gscv = GridSearchCV(
    xgb_clf, param_grid, 
    scoring=success_rate_scorer, 
    n_jobs=-1, cv=kfold, verbose=2)
gs_result = gscv.fit(X_train, y_train)
# the cross-validation process was too long,
# hence left out. After some effort, we choose
# the following parameters
